      {
        "content": "Social media's algorithms prioritize engagement, often amplifying negative content that incites fear, anger, or anxiety, leading to increased stress and depression among users. This constant exposure to harmful material can distort perceptions of reality and self-worth, particularly in vulnerable demographics such as teenagers. Furthermore, the addictive nature of social media, fueled by dopamine-driven feedback loops, contributes to decreased attention spans and impaired face-to-face social skills. Implementing mental health reforms, such as algorithmic transparency, content moderation improvements, and promoting digital literacy, is essential to mitigate these adverse effects and prioritize user wellbeing over profit-driven engagement metrics.",
        "additional_kwargs": {
          "refusal": null
